### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

The purpose of this feature request is to enhance the functionality of the newly proposed `@defer` syntax by introducing a contextual variable, referred to as `$resourceUrl`. This variable will be automatically populated with the import URL of the code that is marked to be deferred loaded.

The primary motivation for introducing the `$resourceUrl` contextual variable within the `@defer ` syntax is to streamline the management of service worker caches.
The presence of an auto-generated and easily accessible `$resourceUrl` mitigates the complexity of keeping a unique identifier refering to the unknown lazy loaded file for example in the indexedDB to identify if the service worker cache was already filled with the specific lazy loaded file.

This feature is expected to have a positive impact on the current workflow by reducing boilerplate code, minimizing errors related to manual URL handling, and standardizing the approach across the entire codebase.


### Proposed solution



In the component code something like the following would be possible

```TypeScript
// my-component.component.ts
@Component({
  ...
  template: `
    <!-- the `on` condition is just exemplary -->
    @defer(when isSWCached($resourceUrl); on viewport) {...}
  `
})
export class MyComponent {
  private messageChannel = new MessageChannel();
  
  constructor() {
	  navigator.serviceWorker.controller.postMessage({
		    type: 'INIT_PORT',
	  }, [this.messageChannel.port2]);
  
  }
  
  isSWCached(resourceUrl: string) {
	  return new Promise(resolve = >{
		  this.messageChannel.port1.onmessage = (event) => {
		    if (event.data.payload.id === resourceUrl) {
			    resolve(coerceBoolean(event.data.payload.isCached));
		    }
		  };
		  this.navigator.serviceWorker.controller.postMessage({
			    type: 'CHECK_CACHE',
			    payload: {
				    id: resourceUrl
			    }
		  });
	  };
  }
}
```

and the related service-worker.js could use the `caches` API directly to respond to the `postMessage`

```js
// service-worker.js
let _port;

// Listen to the CHECK_CACHE message
self.addEventListener('message', (event) => {
if (event.data && event.data.type === 'INIT_PORT') {
    _port = event.ports[0];
}
  
if (event.data && event.data.type === 'CHECK_CACHE') {
	caches.open(cacheName).then(async (cache) => {      
		const cacheResult = await cache.match(event.data.payload.id);
		_port.postMessage({
			payload: {
				isCached: cacheResult !== undefined
			}
		});
	})
  }
});
```


### Alternatives considered

The same can propably be achieved with using indexedDB and a custom unique identifier instead of the `$resourceUrl`, but would be much harder to implement in my opinion.

